ECK120009863	grcAp1	reverse	2716523	Sigma70					tgtgtggtttttattgatttaaatcaaagattcaagggtgtttgaggagtatatatacacTcaagcaacaatggttttacc	ECK12		
ECK120009864	rrsAp1	forward	4035239	Sigma32, Sigma70					cagaaaattattttaaatttcctcttgtcaggccggaataactccctataatgcgccaccActgacacggaacaacggcaa	ECK12	Keener J. and Nomura M. (1996). Regulation of Ribosome Synthesis, in: Neidhardt, F. (Editor in Chief) et al., <i>E. coli</i> and <i>Salmonella</i>. Cellular and Molecular Biology. ASM Press, Washington, D.C.,  p. 1417-1431.<br>Although the organization and sequence of the seven major ribosomal RNA (rRNA) P1 promoters are  highly conserved, the upstream region differs considerably in its regulation, with different transcription factor affinities for the individual upstream regions and strikingly different architectures of the resulting DNA-protein complexes that form with the individual rRNA operon upstream regions <a href="#myRef" class="linkBlue">Hillebrand A, Wurm R, Menzel A, Wagner R,2005</a><br>Based on studies of binding sites determined using gel shift and footprinting analyses with Lrp and H-NS regulator proteins, it was demonstrated that both proteins interact with obvious synergism in the repression of all seven <i>E. coli</i> <i>rrn</i> P1 promoter upstream regions; as a result, they help the efficient shutdown of rRNA synthesis.  Likewise, both proteins could be a transient heteromer via a protein-protein interaction that interferes with the RNA polymerase, and this way it may alter the DNA of the upstream regions of all seven ribosomal P1 promoters <a href="#myRef" class="linkBlue">Pul U,2005</a>.<br>The <i>rrsA</i>p1 is also recognized by &sigma;<sup>32</sup>, which shows a -35 box, spacer, and -10 box, CGGAAT-14-CGCCAC, based on similarity to the consensus sequence of the set of known functional promoters for this &sigma; factor, for which there is strong experimental evidence: high homology; score, 7.24; <i>P</i>-value, 2.35e05.

ECK120009888	motAp	reverse	1977302	Sigma28					accgccatcccgggcagtaaaaagacgtaaactttcccagaatcctgccgatattatcccAcaactgctggatgaacagag	ECK12	The sequence of this promoter has been defined, by computational analyses, from the consensus sequence of the &sigma;<sup>28</sup> (&sigma;<sup>F</sup>) promoters  TAAAGTTT in the -35 box and GCCGATAA in the -10 box <a href="#myRef" class="linkBlue">Park K,2001. Ko M,2000. Ide N,1999</a>. Therefore, we assigned a putative transcription start site for this promoter based on the observation that the majority of the &sigma;<sup>28</sup> promoters, determined experimentally, present an important -10 motif (5'-CGA-3') at the positions -12 to -10 and a distance of 6 nucleotides between the transcription start site and the -10 box  <a href="#myRef" class="linkBlue">Yu HH, Di Russo EG, Rounds MA, Tan M,2006. Yu HH,2006. Park K,2001</a><br>The <i>motA</i>p promoter is an intragenic promoter controlled by FliA, which is inside the <i>flhC</i> gene. The FliA promoter within the <i>flhC</i> gene constrains evolution of the FlhC amino acid sequence. <a href="#myRef" class="linkBlue">Fitzgerald DM, Smith C, Lapierre P, Wade JT,2018</a>  Although FlhC has two amino acids (Ala177 and Asp178) overlapping the -10 region, which are highly conserved among &gamma;-proteobacteria, Asp178 is not required for FlhC function <a href="#myRef" class="linkBlue">Fitzgerald DM, Smith C, Lapierre P, Wade JT,2018</a>  The Ala-Asp motif is conserved due to selective pressure on the <i>motA</i> promoter, rather than on the amino acids themselves <a href="#myRef" class="linkBlue">Fitzgerald DM, Smith C, Lapierre P, Wade JT,2018</a><br><i>motA</i>p, the promoter within the <i>flhC</i> gene, is the most highly conserved of all FliA promoters <a href="#myRef" class="linkBlue">Fitzgerald DM, Smith C, Lapierre P, Wade JT,2018</a><br>

ECK120010154	purEp	reverse	553142	Sigma70					gctgatttcacagccacgcaaccgttttccttgctctctttccgtgctattctctgtgccCtctaaagccgagagttgtgc	ECK12	554 promoter regions from <i>Escherichia coli</i> were aligned in order to analyze their sequence similarities. Mitchell et al. (2003) <a href="#myRef" class="linkBlue">Mitchell JE,2003</a> focused on conservation, patterns, similarities, and differences between promoters with or without an extended -10 5'-TG-3' element and other conserved elements. They experimentally showed that, for several naturally occurring extended -10 promoters, the 5'-TRTG-3' motif is an important determinant for promoter activity. Eleven promoters were selected for further experimental study. Of those, the seven most active (<i>aroF > ompF > envA > purFp1 > purEF > purMN > gyrA</i>) were investigated for the contribution of the extended -10 motif by changing the 5'-TG-3'. Promoters with poor matches to the -10 and -35 consensus hexamers are more dependent on the 5'-TG-3' motif and this plays a similar role on different promoters. The dinucleotide at -17 and -16 in aroFp results in similar patterns of activity, suggesting that these bases play a similar role on different promoters <a href="#myRef" class="linkBlue">Mitchell JE,2003</a>.

ECK120010234	dpsp	reverse	848950	Sigma70, Sigma38					attagtgtgataggaacagccagaatagcggaacacatagccggtgctatacttaatctcGttaattactgggacataaca	ECK12	Results suggest that the <i>dps</i> promoter is recognized by both  the &sigma;<sup>70</sup> holoenzyme and &sigma;<sup>S</sup> holoenzyme, since OxyR acts on &sigma;<sup>70</sup>, and in addition the starts of the OxyR-dependent and the &sigma;<sup>S</sup>-dependent transcripts are identical.  This promoter displays an unusual form of regulation. If cells are treated with hydrogen peroxide during exponential growth, <i>dps</i> transcription is induced by OxyR, which activates &sigma;<sup>70</sup> RNA polymerase. Surprisingly, the same promoter is also  activated by IHF and &sigma;<sup>S</sup> at the onset of the stationary phase. It is assumed that both OxyR and IHF bind upstream of the <i>dps</i> promoter  and that the mechanisms of activation act independently of each other.  The promoter has a a sequence that conforms to the consensus -10, but no obvious -35 sequence is present. Possibly, the <i>dps</i>  promoter is  not ideally bound by either holoenzyme, leading to the need for  IHF to enhance the binding of &sigma;<sup>S</sup> RNA polymerase and of OxyR to enhance the binding  of &sigma;<sup>70</sup> RNA polymerase. <br>The <i>dpS</i> gene is positively regulated by RpoS in stationary phase, and it is mainly controlled at the level of transcription <a href="#myRef" class="linkBlue">Phadtare S,2001</a>. The effect by RpoS is likely indirect and might be mediated by an intermediate regulator that itself is directly regulated by RpoS.  Phadtare  et al. (2001) found that CspC and CspE upregulate the expression of <i>dps</i> by regulating the expression of RpoS itself <a href="#myRef" class="linkBlue">Phadtare S,2001</a>. <br>Fis and H-NS control &sigma; factor selection at the <i>dps</i> promoter <a href="#myRef" class="linkBlue">Grainger DC,2008</a>

ECK120010255	guaBp	reverse	2634107	Sigma70					agcaagcattttttgcaaaaaggggtagatgcaatcggttacgctctgtataatgccgcgGcaatatttattaaccactct	ECK12	The <i>Escherichia coli</i> <i>guaB</i> promoter (PguaB) regulates transcription of the <i>guaBA</i> operon, encoding GuaB and GuaA, which are required for the <i>de novo</i> synthesis of GMP.<br>Between the <i>guaB</i> and <i>guaA</i> genes exists a 68-bp intercistronic region that contains a palindromic sequence and could form a possible &rho;-independent terminator, but the effect of this possible hairpin loop should be modest over the expression of the <i>guaB</i> gene <a href="#myRef" class="linkBlue">Tiedeman AA,1985</a> <br>In 1977, Fukumaki et al. showed that the transcription of the <i>guaA</i> gene can be dependent on a secondary promoter located within the <i>guaB</i> gene, but the precise position was not located <a href="#myRef" class="linkBlue">Fukumaki Y, Shimada K, Takagi Y,1977</a> Evidence to demonstrate this was obtained by using a fago lambda-<i>pguaA</i> transducing phage <a href="#myRef" class="linkBlue">Fukumaki Y, Shimada K, Takagi Y,1977</a> <br>The activity of guaBp is subject to growth rate-dependent control (GRDC), that is, the activity of guaBp increases as a function of the cellular growth rate <a href="#myRef" class="linkBlue">Davies IJ,1996. Husnain SI, Thomas MS,2008. Husnain SI,2008</a> Two elements are required for this regulation, an UP element, located between  -59 and  -38 relative to the <i>guaB</i> transcriptional start site <a href="#myRef" class="linkBlue">Husnain SI, Thomas MS,2008</a> and a binding site for cAMP-CRP, located over 100 bp upstream of the transcription start site. cAMP-CRP, bound to this upstream site, downregulates guaBp. Downregulation is influenced by the growth rate and not by the carbon source <a href="#myRef" class="linkBlue">Husnain SI,2009</a> The UP element, which is also required for GRDC, contains two independent subsites that are able to activate transcription independently. It stimulates <i>guaBA</i> transcription ~8- to 10-fold both <i>in vivo</i> and <i>in vitro</i>, and this activity requires the C-terminal domain of the RNA polymerase &alpha;-subunit <a href="#myRef" class="linkBlue">Husnain SI, Thomas MS,2008</a> The mechanism by which cAMP-CRP together with the UP element regulate transcription in a growth rate-dependent manner is not yet clear.<br>Based on deletion analysis, purified proteins of FIS, and multiple <i>in vitro</i> transcription assays, Husnain and Thomas (2008) <a href="#myRef" class="linkBlue">Husnain SI,2008</a>proved that the putative FIS-binding sites (-126, -109, -92, and -76) located upstream of the guaBp core elements are not functional, since FIS does not bind in these sites, and they were removed from EcoCyc. Binding of FIS to sites FIS I, II, and III (-11, +8, and +29, respectively), identified by Husnain and Thomas (2008), represses transcription from <i>guaBA</i> ~8- to 10-fold <i>in vitro</i> but not <i>in vivo</i> <a href="#myRef" class="linkBlue">Husnain SI,2008</a><br>guaBp is repressed by PurR, and the binding site for PurR overlaps the core promoter <a href="#myRef" class="linkBlue">Husnain SI,2009. Davies IJ,1996</a> Expression of <i>guaB</i> is also repressed by DnaA <i>in vivo</i>. A consensus binding site, located approximately 200 bp downstream from the translation initiation codon, is required for DnaA-mediated repression at guaBp <a href="#myRef" class="linkBlue">Tesfa-Selase F,1996. Tesfa-Selase F,1992</a> The role of a second, nonconsensus DnaA site overlapping the <i>guaB</i> promoter is not yet clear. In addition, guaBp carries a GC-rich discriminator <a href="#myRef" class="linkBlue">Andrews SC, Guest JR,1988</a><br>Neither Fis nor DnaA or PurR is required for GRDC of guaBp <a href="#myRef" class="linkBlue">Husnain SI,2008. Husnain SI,2009</a>

Perhaps this RNA polymerase forms an inactive promoter complex, as happens with the argTp promoter <a href="#myRef" class="linkBlue">Maitra A,2005</a> <br>The presence of eight amino acids (alanine, glutamine, glutamic acid, isoleucine, leucine, methionine, serine, and valine) in the growth medium enhances the activity of the rrnBp1 promoter. <a href="#myRef" class="linkBlue">Zhang X, Liang ST, Bremer H,2006</a>suggested that it is a result of the slow synthesis of one of the enzymes that produces ppGpp (the <i>spoT</i> gene product).<br>Although the organization and sequence of the seven major ribosomal RNA (rRNA) P1 promoters are  highly conserved, the upstream region differs considerably in its regulation, with different transcription factor affinities for the individual upstream regions and strikingly different architectures of the resulting DNA-protein complexes that form with the individual rRNA operon upstream regions <a href="#myRef" class="linkBlue">Hillebrand A, Wurm R, Menzel A, Wagner R,2005</a><br>Based on studies of binding sites with gel shift and footprinting with Lrp and H-NS regulator proteins, it was demonstrated that both proteins interact with obvious synergism in the repression of all seven <i>E. coli</i> <i>rrn</i> P1 promoter upstream regions; as a result, they help the efficient shutdown of rRNA synthesis. ECK120010571	cvpAp1	reverse	2430800	Sigma70					attgatgcgcgggaaggaaatccctacgcaaacgttttctttttctgttagaatgcgcccCgaacaggatgacagggcgta	ECK12	554 promoter regions from <i>Escherichia coli</i> were aligned in order to analyze their sequence similarities. Mitchell et al. (2003) <a href="#myRef" class="linkBlue">Mitchell JE,2003</a> focused on conservation, patterns, similarities, and differences between promoters with or without an extended -10 5'-TG-3' element and other conserved elements. They experimentally showed that, for several naturally occurring extended -10 promoters, the 5'-TRTG-3' motif is an important determinant for promoter activity. Eleven promoters were selected for further experimental study. Of those, the seven most active (<i>aroF > ompF > envA > purFp1 > purEF > purMN > gyrA</i>) were investigated about the contribution of the extended -10 motif by changing the 5'-TG-3'. Promoters with poor matches to the -10 and -35 consensus hexamers are more dependent on the 5'-TG-3' motif, and this plays a similar role on different promoters. The dinucleotide at -17 and -16 in aroFp results in similar patterns of activity, suggesting that these bases play a similar role on different promoters <a href="#myRef" class="linkBlue">Mitchell JE,2003</a>.

ECK120010992	aroFp	reverse	2741201	Sigma70					gtaaataaaaatgtacgaaatatggattgaaaactttactttatgtgttatcgttacgtcAtcctcgctgaggatcaacta	ECK12	A total of 554 promoter regions from <i>Escherichia coli</i> were aligned in order to analyze their sequence similarities.  <a href="#myRef" class="linkBlue">Mitchell JE,2003</a>focused on conservation, patterns, similarities, and differences between promoters with or without an extended -10 5'-TG-3' element and other conserved elements. They experimentally showed that, for several naturally occurring extended -10 promoters, the 5'-TRTG-3' motif is an important determinant for promoter activity. Eleven promoters were selected for further experimental study. Of those, the seven most active (<i>aroF</i> > <i>ompF</i> > <i>envA</i> > <i>purFp1</i> > <i>purEF</i> > <i>purMN</i> > <i>gyrA</i>) were investigated for the contribution of the extended -10 motif by changing the 5'-TG-3' element. Promoters with poor matches to the -10 and -35 consensus hexamers are more dependent on the 5'-TG-3' motif, and this plays a similar role on different promoters. The dinucleotide at -17 and -16 in <i>aroF</i>p results in similar patterns of activity, suggesting that these bases play a similar role on different promoters <a href="#myRef" class="linkBlue">Mitchell JE,2003</a>

ECK120011008	ompFp	reverse	987092	Sigma38, Sigma70					ctttatctttgtagcactttcacggtagcgaaacgttagtttgaatggaaagatgcctgcAgacacataaagacaccaaac	ECK12	Porin regulation by the CpxA-CpxR system and by the EnvZ-OmpR system converges at the porin promoters <a href="#myRef" class="linkBlue">Batchelor E,2005</a>. <br>The OmpR transcriptional factor cooperatively binds to the sites of the upstream regions from the ompFp promoter in a discontinuous  galloping  manner, as described by <a href="#myRef" class="linkBlue">Yoshida T,2006</a> <br>554 promoter regions from <i>Escherichia coli</i> were aligned in order to analyze their sequence similarities. Mitchell et al. (2003) <a href="#myRef" class="linkBlue">Mitchell JE,2003</a> focused on conservation, patterns, similarities, and differences between promoters with or without an extended -10 5'-TG-3' element and other conserved elements. They experimentally showed that, for several naturally occurring extended -10 promoters, the 5'-TRTG-3' motif is an important determinant for promoter activity. Eleven promoters were selected for further experimental study. Of those, the seven most active (<i>aroF > ompF > envA > purFp1 > purEF > purMN > gyrA</i>) were investigated for the contribution of the extended -10 motif by changing the 5'-TG-3' motif. Promoters with poor matches to the -10 and -35 consensus hexamers are more dependent on the 5'-TG-3' motif, and this plays a similar role on different promoters. The dinucleotide at -17 and -16 in aroFp results in similar patterns of activity, suggesting that these bases play a similar role on different promoters <a href="#myRef" class="linkBlue">Mitchell JE,2003</a>.

ECK120033733	lpxCp1	forward	106508	Sigma70					gctgattaagaattgactggaatttgggtttcgaggctctttgtgctaaactggcccgccGaatgtatagtacacttcggt	ECK12	554 promoter regions from <i>Escherichia coli</i> were aligned in order to analyze their sequence similarities. Mitchell et al. (2003) <a href="#myRef" class="linkBlue">Mitchell JE,2003</a> focused on conservation, patterns, similarities, and differences between promoters with or without an extended -10 5'-TG-3' element and other conserved elements. They experimentally showed that, for several naturally occurring extended -10 promoters, the 5'-TRTG-3' motif is an important determinant for promoter activity. Eleven promoters were selected for further experimental study. Of those, the seven most active (<i>aroF > ompF > envA > purFp1 > purEF > purMN > gyrA</i>) were investigated regarding the contribution of the extended -10 motif by changing the 5'-TG-3' element. Promoters with poor matches to the -10 and -35 consensus hexamers are more dependent on the 5'-TG-3' motif, and this plays a similar role in different promoters. The dinucleotide at -17 and -16 in aroFp results in similar patterns of activity, suggesting that these bases play a similar role in different promoters <a href="#myRef" class="linkBlue">Mitchell JE,2003</a>.
